<P>
BASEBALL DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE MAJORS; GROIN PULL PUTS MARLINS' HARVEY ON DL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Florida Marlin closer Bryan Harvey, bothered by a pulled right groin, was 
placed on the 15-day disabled list, retroactive to June 30. . . . The Red Sox 
activated second baseman Tim Naehring from the disabled list and sent pitcher 
Nate Minchey to Pawtucket of the International League. Naehring was batting 
.287 in 174 at-bats when he went on the disabled list June 10 with a sprained 
right ankle. . . . Bob Watson, general manager of the Houston Astros, underwent 
successful surgery for removal of his cancerous prostate gland at a St. Louis 
hospital.Watson, 48, was expected to remain hospitalized for five days before 
returning to Houston. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Baseball players declined to make contract proposals to owners and said their 
executive board might not set a strike deadline when it meets Monday. Because 
players are fearful owners will unilaterally impose a salary cap after the 
season, the union is considering a walk out in August or September. . . . 
Chicago Cub broadcaster Harry Caray was expected to be released today from a 
Chicago hospital, where he underwent heart tests and observation after 
collapsing June 23 at Miami's Joe Robbie Stadium. 
</P>
