<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / QUARTERFINALS; SPOTLIGHT; DUTCH MUST HAVE THING ABOUT 
SECURITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS DUFRESNE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Before getting in trouble at the Orlando airport, Muller, who had also been 
contributing articles to the Orlando Sentinel, refused to take part in a media 
security check when departing the Citrus Bowl after Monday's game. 
</P>
<P>
 All reporters were subjected to the search. 
</P>
<P>
 "We did not allow it," Muller wrote for Tuesday's Sentinel editions. "I was 
surprised and upset that they would want to do this. Why should we open our bag 
when we leave the stadium? This is an experience I have not had in my 20 years 
covering soccer." 
</P>
<P>
 Muller was just warming up. 
</P>
<P>
 "They tried to explain that someone stole something in the stadium, and that 
was the cause for the check. That is a pity, but it is not a reason to control 
all the media. It is their failure, not our guilt." 
</P>
<P>
 And this: 
</P>
<P>
 "It also is the responsibility of the host committee to watch out for the 
security of the stadium. I can swear that I would never steal something in a 
stadium, and if I ever did, it would be the whole stadium." 
</P>
<P>
 In closing: 
</P>
<P>
 "In spite of the incident, I enjoyed my stay in Orlando." CHRIS DUFRESNE 
</P>
</TEXT>
