<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL DAILY REPORT; ANGELS; FREAK ACCIDENT RATTLES DISARCINA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Angel shortstop Gary DiSarcina took no chances Wednesday. Prompted by an 
accident Tuesday, he wore batting gloves, for the first time this season, in 
the game against the Boston Red Sox.  
</P>
<P>
 DiSarcina's bat flew out of his hands in the ninth inning Tuesday and hit two 
young boys, one of whom spent the night in critical condition with a skull 
fracture. The boy was listed in serious condition on Wednesday, according to 
hospital officials. 
</P>
<P>
 Andrew Schellekes, 8, of Gilmanton, N.H., spent the night in intensive care 
after going into shock, and also had a three-inch gash over his right eye. His 
cousin, Matthew O'Connor, 10, also suffered cuts and was held overnight for 
observation.  
</P>
<P>
 Angel General Manager Bill Bavasi and assistant Tim Mead visited the boys and 
their parents Wednesday, and Manager Marcel Lachemann called them. It was the 
first time either youngster had attended a major league game and they had moved 
to vacant seats closer to the field after the seventh inning. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was pretty much a helpless feeling," DiSarcina said. "I let the bat slip 
out of my hands a couple of times, but nothing like that ever happened. . . . 
My dad went to security officials and got the names and addresses. I'm going to 
send some stuff to them when I get back." 
</P>
<P>
 Security officials said both teams sent over souvenirs. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels have decided that they will bring up reliever Scott Lewis from 
triple-A Vancouver by July 15. He's expected to replace Craig Lefferts, who has 
allowed 62 baserunners in 34 2/3 innings, yielding a team-high .350 batting 
average. 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels also are exploring the possibility of recalling Troy Percival, who 
has 10 saves for Vancouver. Percival, considered to be the Angels' closer of 
the future when they didn't protect Bryan Harvey, is fully recovered from 
reconstructive elbow surgery of a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
 Also, Lachemann said Vancouver starter Andrew Lorraine (9-3, 3.24 earned-run 
average) is ready to be called up to the big leagues whenever they need him. 
Lorraine could be used in the bullpen, Lachemann said. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Angel pitching coach Chuck Hernandez, whose newborn baby remains in intensive 
care, is expected to rejoin the team Friday in New York. His wife, Donna, is 
expected to be released from the hospital today. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Angel third baseman Spike Owen hit a foul ball off his right heel in the 
seventh inning and is expected to miss a couple of games. BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</TEXT>
