<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA NIGUEL; BUDGET CUTS SPENDING BUT NOT CITY SERVICES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council gave final approval this week to a $16.3-million budget for 
the next fiscal year that decreases spending while maintaining or expanding 
current services. 
</P>
<P>
 Spending is down 18% from last year's budget, primarily in the area of major 
park and street improvements due to the completion of the $3.3-million Sea 
Country Senior and Community Center, which opened June 25. 
</P>
<P>
 One of this year's main projects in that portion of the budget will be the 
creation of Colinas de Capistrano Park at a cost of $175,000. 
</P>
<P>
 Police services spending will increase by 1% in fiscal year 1994-1995, as the 
city pays $213,000 for two additional sheriff's deputies to patrol Laguna 
Niguel. Police Chief Joseph Davis said the two new deputies are needed because 
of population growth and increased commercial development in the city. 
</P>
<P>
 In approving the budget, the council authorized spending $35,000 to implement 
a "Shop Laguna Niguel" marketing program along with the Laguna Niguel Chamber 
of Commerce.  
</P>
<P>
 Casey said the city expects property tax revenue to fall by $120,000, but 
sales tax revenue to rise by $200,000 thanks to the opening of several new 
restaurants and a Mervyn's department store. 
</P>
<P>
 The council also appropriated $200,000 to be used for planning studies on 
future uses of the El Toro Marine Corps Air Station, in conjunction with other 
South County cities. Any specific use of the money in that fund will have to be 
approved by the council. LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
