<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: SECURITIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 SEC, Industry Discuss Derivatives Guidelines: As Congress tries to craft rules 
to rein in the derivatives business, the Securities and Exchange Commission is 
discussing voluntary guidelines with six of the nation's largest derivatives 
dealers.The genesis of the talks is an April letter to the SEC from the 
Securities Industry Assn., Wall Street's main trade group. It proposes periodic 
reporting to the SEC or other regulators about derivatives risks; industry 
standards for investor protection; capital standards, and financial statement 
disclosure for derivatives. The SEC talks involve CS First Boston, Goldman 
Sachs & Co., Salomon Inc., Merrill Lynch & Co., Lehman Brothers and Morgan 
Stanley & Co. None of the firms would comment on the discussions. 
</P>
